2. Treta Yuga (The Silver Age)

Duration: 1,296,000 Human Years
Theme: The Age of Sacrifice (Virtue declines by 25%)
Dominant Quality: Rajas (Passion, Activity)

The "Bull of Dharma" now stands on three legs. Humanity begins to lose its inherent enlightenment, requiring kings and rituals to stay righteous.

The Power Vacuum: From Humble Steps to Bloody Axes

The Three Paces (Vamana): The demon-king Bali, though righteous, conquers the heavens. Vishnu appears as the dwarf Vamana, asking for three paces of land. In his cosmic form, he steps over the universe, pushing Bali to the underworld. However, Bali's removal leaves the earthly kings (Kshatriyas) without a rival, and they quickly spiral into arrogance and tyranny.

The 21 Purges (Parashurama): To check the corrupt kings, Vishnu descends as Parashurama. He slaughters the tyrannical warrior class twenty-one times. But this bloodbath leaves the world without any rulers at all—the "loop" of chaos can only be closed by a King who rules not by the axe, but by the code of honor.

The Epic of the Ideal: The Ramayana

The Exile Loop: Lord Rama is born to be the perfect King, but on the eve of his coronation, a forgotten promise leads to his 14-year exile. This exile isn't just a punishment; it is a setup. In the forest, the demon-king Ravana abducts Rama's wife, Sita.

The Ten-Headed Shadow: Ravana, a scholar-king who mastered the Vedas but succumbed to ego, represents the ultimate challenge to Dharma. Rama’s journey to Lanka, the building of the bridge, and the final war are all steps toward defining the "Ideal Man."

The Bittersweet Return: Rama defeats Ravana and restores Ram Rajya, but the age ends with a lingering question of public duty versus personal love, as Sita returns to the earth from which she was born.
